For example, when we take meeting notes and someone has the action to do something, we can't be in the business of reviewing all of them. So it would be great if we could type in the search box "@alert" (for example) and get a calendar popup that will allow us to set a date/time for which we'll get a reminder. Perhaps even the option for a recurring alert.

See [RUN-124|https://bobswift.atlassian.net/browse/RUN-124] for a problem reported on extranet.atlassian.com. This problem surfaced on Confluence 5.3, earlier releases appear to be fine. Use your own extranet example or here is a simple one to reproduce (requires Run Plugin for Confluence obviously):
{noformat}
{run:replace=xxx:aaa+bbb ccc}
xxx: $xxx
request_string: $request_string
{run}
{noformat}
The request string shows what the resulting url should look like. If you look at live headers, for instance, you will see the correct request string first and then later another encoding is done on the + to get to %2B. Now on decoding, both the original + and the blank will decode to + which is incorrect.

The use of blanks in variables is *very* common and the use of links (like you are doing on your site) is also common.

